article.headline: Arenas leads Wizards with triple-double
article.linkText: Nash hurts shoulder in Mavericks' loss
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Wizards beat Dallas at its own game, mainly because the Mavericks couldn't keep up without starting point guard Steve Nash. Gilbert Arenas had 25 points, 12 rebounds and 10 assists, and the Wizards capitalized on a shoulder injury to Nash in a 100-90 victory Wednesday night. "We wanted to show the NBA that we can be as up-tempo, athletic and aggressive as the Dallas Mavericks," Wizards coach Eddie Jordan said. "They're a team we admire because they play a fun, wide-open game, they have scorers all over the place and create different mismatches." It's a wonderful formula when all the pieces are in place. But the Mavericks aren't the same without Nash, who leads the team in assists and ranks third in scoring. Nash played only seven minutes, contributing two points and two assists before leaving in the first quarter with a strained left shoulder. He is listed as doubtful for Thursday night's game at Toronto. "It got real sore in the first couple minutes of the game, and the rest of the quarter it just got sorer and sorer -- every possession, every movement, every bump," Nash said. "When I came out, I couldn't even make certain movements at all, so there was really no way I could contribute." Without Nash, the Mavericks fell behind by 16 at halftime and never made a serious run in the second half. "We haven't played without Nash in a long, long time, and that's just too much to ask," Dallas coach Don Nelson said. The game drew 17,455 on a rainy night, ending the Wizards' run of 83 straight sellouts -- a streak that began during the Michael Jordan era in Washington. Throughout his tenure in the nation's capital, Jordan could not accomplish what Arenas did: Washington's first triple-double since Rod Strickland in April 1999. "I'm an assassin with the ball," Arenas said. "I rebounded, dished the ball, scored. Like a point guard -- like a Jason Kidd or Gary Payton -- I just helped the team win." Larry Hughes scored 19 points, and Christian Laettner had 13 points and 13 rebounds in Washington's first home win against Dallas in six tries since March 1997. "We want to do things that people think we can't do," said Hughes, who accounted for five of the Wizards' club-record 13 3-pointers. "We started off in man-to-man and we couldn't really guard them," Dallas center Dirk Nowitzki said. "When we tried to play them zone, there were holes in the zone. They found them and made a lot of 3s." Antawn Jamison scored 21 points off the bench and Antoine Walker had 18 for the Mavericks, whose three-game winning streak ended. "Just because we won a few games, it doesn't disguise the fact that we have work to do, and it shows," Nelson said. Washington opened the second half with a 9-2 run to go up 68-45. After Dallas closed to 81-70 early in the fourth quarter, Juan Dixon hit a driving layup, Hughes made a jumper and Jarvis Hayes added a 3-pointer for an 88-70 lead. After that, the only suspense was if Arenas would complete the triple-double. He did it with an assist on a dunk by Hayes with 3:48 remaining. Arenas scored 12 points on 6-for-9 shooting in the first quarter to help the Wizards take a 30-25 lead. It was 34-29 before Dixon hit a 3-pointer and two layups to spark a 12-4 run that put Washington up by 13. After Dallas closed to 54-43, Arenas hit a reverse layup and Kwame Brown banked a 3-pointer off the glass from the top of the key. The buzzer-beater was Brown's first career 3-pointer in three NBA seasons.

Game notes
After the game, the Wizards announced they had acquired G Brevin Knight from Phoenix for C Jahidi White. ... Wizards F Jerry Stackhouse, on the injured list with a knee injury, turned 29 Wednesday. ... Dallas had won three straight and seven of nine against the Wizards.
